         <div type="edition" xml:lang="la" resp="#JP">
            <ab>               
               <lb n="1"/><persName><name><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Iu</supplied>llius</name> <name>Illyricus</name></persName> ·
               <lb n="2"/><persName><name><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Vet</supplied>ihe</name> <name>Gratia</name></persName> filie <g type="hedera"/>
               <lb n="3"/><persName><name><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Sabini</supplied>aneti</name></persName> carissime · 
               <lb n="4"/><g type="cupa"/><g type="aviscumramo"/><g type="guttus"/><g type="calix"/><!-- this needs modifying -->
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
            <p><!--external apparatus criticus (if applicable)--></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
            <p>Iullius Illyricus (and) Vettia Gratia (set this up) for their beloved daughter Sabiniane.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#SA">
            <p>Iullius Illirico (e) Vettia Gratia (lo edificarono) per la loro amata figlia Sabiniane.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
            <p>The left part of the inscription was lost before it reached Catania, but the missing text (here underlined) and the image of a barrel are recorded by antiquarian writers. Christian epitaphs often included symbolic images, of which the bird holding an olive branch is among the most common. A second inscription from the same cemetery records the death also of Iullius’ and Vettia’s son, Iulius Navigius, aged 16.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" xml:lang="it">
            <p></p>
         </div>
